natural problem: Let $f(x) = \frac{2x+9}{x-7}.$ Find the product of all solutions to the equation $f(f(x)) = x.$
natural solution: We have \[\begin{aligned} f(f(x)) &= f\left(\frac{2x+9}{x-7}\right) \\ &= \frac{2 \cdot \frac{2x+9}{x-7} + 9}{\frac{2x+9}{x-7} - 7} \\ &= \frac{2(2x+9) + 9(x-7)}{(2x+9) - 7(x-7)} \\ &= \frac{13x - 45}{-5x + 58}.\end{aligned}\]Therefore, the equation $f(f(x)) = x$ becomes \[13x - 45 = -5x^2 + 58x,\]or \[5x^2 - 45x - 45 = 0.\]By Vieta's formulas, the product of the solutions to this equation is $\frac{-45}{5},$ or $\boxed{-9}.$
